Perfect — Vite + React + MDX is actually simpler than Next.js because Vite supports **dynamic imports and ESM natively**. Here’s how you can set it up cleanly for your use case.

---

## 1. Prerequisites

Install MDX support for Vite:

```bash
npm install @mdx-js/react vite-plugin-mdx
```

Then in `vite.config.js`:

```js
import { defineConfig } from 'vite';
import react from '@vitejs/plugin-react';
import mdx from 'vite-plugin-mdx';

export default defineConfig({
  plugins: [react(), mdx()]
});
```

---

## 2. File Structure

```
/src
  /projects
    ps-booking.mdx
    tenderhub.mdx
    niloyd.mdx
  /components
    Projects.jsx
```

Each `.mdx` can be full Markdown with React components inside.

---

## 3. Dynamic Import in Vite

Vite supports **`import.meta.glob`**, which is perfect for dynamically loading files.

```jsx
import React, { Suspense } from "react";
import { MDXProvider } from "@mdx-js/react";

const Projects = () => {
  // Glob all MDX files in /projects
  const modules = import.meta.glob("../projects/*.mdx");

  // Load all modules dynamically
  const [projectComponents, setProjectComponents] = React.useState([]);

  React.useEffect(() => {
    const loadProjects = async () => {
      const loaded = await Promise.all(
        Object.values(modules).map(async (mod) => {
          const module = await mod();
          return module.default; // MDX component
        })
      );
      setProjectComponents(loaded);
    };

    loadProjects();
  }, []);

  return (
    <MDXProvider>
      <div className="projects-container">
        {projectComponents.map((Project, i) => (
          <Suspense fallback={<div>Loading project...</div>} key={i}>
            <Project />
          </Suspense>
        ))}
      </div>
    </MDXProvider>
  );
};

export default Projects;
```

---

### ✅ How This Works

1. `import.meta.glob("../projects/*.mdx")` gives you an object mapping file paths → import functions.
2. We dynamically `await mod()` for each file and grab `module.default`, which is the MDX as a React component.
3. Each MDX file renders like a normal React component.
4. `Suspense` provides a fallback while loading — optional but good UX.

---

### 4. Optional: Add Props to MDX

If your MDX files export frontmatter, e.g.,

```mdx
---
title: "PlayStation Booking"
date: "2026-01-20"
---

# Project Overview
...
```

You can access it via:

```js
const module = await mod();
console.log(module.frontmatter.title);
```

Then you could render a **list dynamically with metadata**.

